**Applying the Decision Tree: Q1 Analysis**

As instructed, I've approached this task as an expert in claim framing, focusing on the first question (Q1) of a 12-step decision tree. My goal was to analyze each text segment and determine if it contained an intensifier or comparative adjective directly modifying a risk-adjective, or the fixed idiom "deadly from the start/outset".

I carefully reviewed each segment, applying my knowledge of risk-related language and rhetorical techniques. I paid close attention to the specific criteria of Q1, which includes only the following risk-adjectives: "deadly," "dangerous," "severe," and "critical" when directly modified by an intensifier or comparative. I also remembered to exclude the technical term "highly pathogenic avian influenza (HPAI)" unless further alarmist cues are present and to ignore verbs and adjectives that are not on the list.

My analysis led me to conclude that none of the segments met the specific requirements of Q1. Even when "deadly" was present (segments 6 and 9), it was not directly modified by an intensifier or comparative. I had to focus exclusively on that condition.

